<TITLE> Philippine force storms hotel holding rebel troops </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MANILA, Nov 29 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Renegade Philippine soldiers said on Thursday they would leave a Manila hotel after elite forces battered down the door and fired tear gas into the lobby. "We are going out for the sake of the safety of everybody," said Senator Antonio Trillanes, who led a failed mutiny in 2003 against President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo. "We have been witness and victims of the kind of ruthlessness this administration is giving to the people. Like soldiers we are going to face this," he told reporters. About two dozen rebel soldiers had earlier walked out of their own trial for the 2003 mutiny, escorted by guards assigned to keep them from escaping. They marched to the Peninsula Hotel in Manila's Makati financial district and took over the lobby, calling for the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo. Elite forces were seen swarming outside the teargas-filled lobby after at least one armoured personnel carrier broke through the hotel's front doors. A number of journalists and hotel staff had been trapped in the hotel. It was unclear how many guests, if any, were still in their hotel rooms. The rebel soldiers, who had earlier stopped people from leaving the hotel lobby as a 3 p.m. (0700 GMT) deadline for them to end their mutiny passed, later relented and allowed them to go out. Arroyo, deeply unpopular due to long-running corruption allegations, has survived at least two coup plots and three impeachment bids because of a jaded middle class sick of political instability, and a strong majority in the lower hou
